go-msmpeg4 — pure-Go Microsoft MPEG-4 (v1/v2/v3, DIV3/MP42/…) decoder
Copyright (c) 2026 Oleksandr Zhabotynskyi

PURPOSE — EDUCATIONAL / RESEARCH (WORK IN PROGRESS)
--------------------------------------------------
This is an educational and research project, with two goals:

  1. A clean-room reverse-engineering study of an old, undocumented video format.
  2. A study of how Large Language Models (LLMs) perform at programming and
     reverse-engineering hard, open-ended problems — much of the work here was
     produced by an LLM, and the dead-ends are kept on purpose as part of the record.

It is NOT a production decoder and does not yet decode real-encoder DIV3 files
correctly (see README). For a working MS-MPEG4 / DIV3 decoder use instead:

  * FFmpeg (GPL/LGPL) — https://ffmpeg.org/  ·  https://github.com/FFmpeg/FFmpeg
  * Microsoft's original codec (mpg4c32.dll / Windows Media MPEG-4 V3).

This package decodes only and cannot encode MS-MPEG4.

PROVENANCE OF THE COMMITTED TABLES
----------------------------------
The Microsoft MPEG-4 bitstream format is undocumented. The VLC tables, escape
coding, quantisation, scan and prediction rules COMMITTED in this package were
derived by BLACK-BOX reverse engineering of the bitstream:

  * The ffmpeg ENCODER was fed controlled pixel blocks and the resulting bits were
    observed; the ffmpeg DECODER was used only as a pixel oracle.
  * For the undocumented `ac_pred=1` quirk (which the ffmpeg encoder cannot emit),
    the original MS codec (DivX 3.11 / mpg4c32.dll) was RUN as a black box — never
    disassembled or decompiled.
  * No FFmpeg (or other library) SOURCE CODE is copied into this package. The
    committed tables (`re/data/*.json`, the Go `*_table.go` files) are regenerated
    from crafted bitstreams by the `re/` scripts. FFmpeg's msmpeg4 code is LGPL and
    is not the basis for the committed tables.

  Honesty note: during the (still incomplete) investigation the FFmpeg source and
  the open standards below were also consulted as references to understand the
  format. That informed the analysis, but no code or table data was copied in.

Standard, openly-published references used:
  * ITU-T H.263
  * ISO/IEC 14496-2 (MPEG-4 Part 2)

The reproducible derivation is documented in `re/NOTES.md`, and the generator
scripts in `re/` regenerate each table from crafted bitstreams as evidence.
